recommended for The crop requires 4 - 6 irrigations depending on the soil type and rainfall. Wheat crop requires minimum of 5 irrigations at the following critical stages.
I – Immediately after sowing
II – Crown root intiation : 15-20 DAS 
III- Active tillering stage : 35-40 DAS
IV- Flowering stage : 50-55 DAS
V- Grain filling stage : 70-75 DAS
Crown root initiation and flowering are the most critical stages. Water stagnation should be voided at the time of germination.

KCCAns: Usually, during the rainy season the need for irrigation of mung beans does not require irrigation. However, during this period, due to a long period of rainfall after one year or a shortage of moisture, a light irrigation is necessary when the beans are formed. In the spring and summer, irrigation is required for 10-15 days intervals. Irrigation should be stopped 15 days before harvesting. If there is excess rain in the rainy season or the water is filled with water, then the extra water should be removed from the field, which keeps the air communication in the soil.

KCCAns:
Representative sampling aggregation method-

1- Visit the field in which the sampling is to be done by jig-jig and mark it at 10-15 places so that all parts of the farm can be included in it.

2- Remove debris, debris etc. from the upper surface on the selected places.

3- 15 cm at all these places (6-9 inch) dig deeper V shaped cord. Cleansing the pot from the top of the scalp, up to 2 cm from the top. Remove the thick soil from the bottom and put it in a clean bucket or tray.

4- Mix the collected clay well with the hands and put on clean clothes and make a round pile. Remove the clay from the finger to the four equal parts and remove the soil separately. Now mix the remaining two parts again and make the rounds. Repeat this procedure till almost half of the remains are left in the soil. This representative will be sample.

5- Keep the dry soil sample in a clean plastic bag and put it in a garment bag. An information sheet along with the sample on which all the information is written, put it in a plastic bag and outside the clothes bag.

6- Now send these prepared samples to the soil testing laboratory.

Soil investigation information sheet

KCCAns: Irrigation should be done immediately after harvesting of Kharif season crop, otherwise the possibility of delaying the plant will delay the irrigation. When the monsoon is harvested on the onion crop grown in Kharif season, irrigation should be done as per the requirement. It should be noted that there should be no shortage of water at the time of construction of Shalkankanda, because it is a revolutionary state of the onion crop, because in this stage there is a shortage of yield due to lack of water, while the excess amount of water purple smear (Pillar Batch) invites disease. The farm should not be dry for a long time, otherwise the Shalankand will burst and the crop will come soon, resulting in less production. Therefore, light irrigation should be done from 8-10 days intervals as required. If the water in the field stops due to excess rainfall or other reason then it should be arranged to remove it quickly, otherwise the chances of fungal growth are increased in the crop.

KCCAns:
Vermi Compost

Friend of earthworm farmers and the intestines of land are called. This concentrated substance spreads humus and soil into other layers inside the ground. This leads to soil pollution and increased air traffic and increased storage capacity. The chemical action and the action of microbes in the stomach of earthworms increases the availability of nitrogen, phosphor and potash and other subtle elements found in the soil. Vermi compost does not contain stench and flies and mosquitoes do not grow and the atmosphere is not polluted. By controlling the temperature, the bacteria are active and active. Vermi compost is ready within a month and a half. It contains 2.5 to 3% nitrogen, 1.5 to 2% phosphor and 1.5 to 2% potash is found.

Preparation Method:

To prepare the compost from the waste is to make the pieces of glass and metal pieces separately, and after this, a 10x4 ft platform is prepared to prepare the Vermi compost up to 6 to 12 inches high. Two ridges are added above this platform and huts are made for shade above the platform. Dry fodder on the platform, 3-4 quintals of dung manure and 7-8 quintals of garbage (Garvage) Which is irrigated by the Jhara for 10-15 days to reduce the temperature of the compost fertilizer. After this, 100 thousand square feet are left to the extent of 10 thousand earthworms. After leaving the ketchu, the stitches are covered with jute sacks, and they keep irrigation for 4 days so that 45-50 percent moisture is maintained. Keep in mind that due to excessive wetness the air will be blocked and microbes and earthworms will not be able to die or work.

After 45 days irrigation is stopped and jute bags are removed. After removing the brood, the top manure dries up and the earthworms go into humidity below. Then separate the dry Vermic compost of the above. After 4-5 days, the upper manure of the stitches is dried and the dry manure is separated from the top. Thus, the entire compost separates from the stitches in 3-4 times and in the last the earthworms survive, whose number In the stitches in 2 months, the number of earthworms inserted doubles, keep in mind that do not use gastric, spade or cracks to remove manure from hand. The manure taken from the strains is dried and filtered in shade and stored in a shady place. The quantity of Vermi compost requires 100 grams, one kilogram of one year plants and 6-8 quintals per acre in the crop. Using Vermicum Wash, it would be good to have two exhaust drains on the platform to collect the worm wash.

1- Visit the field in which sampling is to be done by jig-jig and mark it at 10-15 places so that all parts of the farm can be included in it.

2- Remove debris, debris etc. from the upper surface on the selected places.

3- 15 cm at all these places (6-9 inch) dig deeper V shaped cord. Cleansing the pot from the top of the scalp, up to 2 cm from the top. Remove the thick soil from the bottom and put it in a clean bucket or tray.

4- Mix the collected clay well with hand and make a round pile by putting it on clean clothes. Remove the clay from finger to four equal parts and remove the soil separately. Now mix the remaining two parts again and make the rounds. Repeat this procedure until almost half of the remains are left in the soil. This representative will be sample.

5- Keep the dry soil sample in a clean plastic bag and put it in a garment bag. Insert a notice sheet with a sample on which all the information is written, inside a plastic bag and outside a garment bag.

6- Now send these prepared samples to the soil testing laboratory.
